## Quiz

?? At resonance, what is the phase relationship between the current and the source voltage? Why does this matter?
>> They are **in phase**. Because $X_L$ and $X_C$ cancel, the circuit behaves like a pure resistor. All power delivered by the source is real (dissipated in $R$) — none is stored and returned by the reactive elements on a cycle-average basis. This is why resonant circuits are used to pick out a single frequency: off-resonance, the current is small *and* phase-shifted.

?? Halving the capacitance (C → C/2) moves the resonant frequency where, and by how much?
>> $\omega_0 = 1/\sqrt{LC}$, so halving $C$ multiplies $\omega_0$ by $\sqrt{2} \approx 1.41$. The new resonance is at $\sim 225\text{ Hz}$ instead of $159\text{ Hz}$.

?? If we increase $R$ (say from 10 Ω to 100 Ω), what happens to the peak current at resonance and to the "sharpness" of the resonance curve?
>> Peak current drops 10× (since $I_\text{peak} = V_0/R$ at $\omega_0$). The quality factor $Q = \omega_0 L / R$ also drops 10× (from 10 to 1), so the resonance curve becomes **much broader** — the bandwidth $\Delta\omega = \omega_0/Q$ grows 10×. High $Q$ = sharp, selective filter; low $Q$ = broad, poor selectivity.
